tonight, the health department will testify before the city council along with other city agencies on gun violence reduction efforts. as our post yesterday noted, “the research is clear – violence causes trauma, and trauma causes violence.”
waverly and surrounding communities, we hope to see you tomorrow!
check back later this week as we share more about our programs for baltimore city residents, and for interviews with staff engaged in trauma-based work in the department! bmorehealthy

a broader focus involves ensuring that a systems-based approach supports residents through providing education about the harmful effects of trauma and violence and collaborating across multiple systems and disciplines to share interventions to interrupt the cycle of violence.
creating a safe space for children to learn and thrive and for adults to work and socialize can also support positive well-being.

a focus on prevention, healing, and recovery is part of a public health approach toward well-being and overall health and wellness. increasing protective factors can have positive effects for developing resiliency, especially in children.
unaddressed, these poor health outcomes can impact a person’s ability to be productive at work and interact socially with friends and family.

from a public health perspective, childhood trauma is directly linked to poor adult health outcomes such as: chronic disease, depression, self-harm and suicide, and risky sexual behavior among many others.
this week, the baltimore city health department will highlight our work surrounding trauma and its relationship to violence. the research is clear—violence causes trauma, and trauma causes violence.
